CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 Public Ethics – Members of the General Assembly – State and Local Government
3 Employment Exemption
4 FOR the purpose of exempting authorizing the Joint Committee on Legislative Ethics to
5 exempt a member of the General Assembly, a filed candidate for election to the
6 General Assembly, or a member–elect of the General Assembly from the prohibition
7 against receiving earned income from an executive unit or political subdivision of the
8 State under certain circumstances; requiring the Committee to issue a certain
9 opinion; and generally relating to earned income by members of the General
10 Assembly, filed candidates for election to the General Assembly, and members–elect
11 of the General Assembly.
12 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
13 Article – General Provisions
14 Section 5–514(a)
15 Annotated Code of Maryland
16 (2019 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
17 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
18 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
19 Article – General Provisions
20 5–514.
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0618*

2 SENATE BILL 618
1 (a) (1) Except as provided in paragraph (2) or (3) of this subsection, a member
2 of the General Assembly, a filed candidate for election to the General Assembly, or a
3 member–elect of the General Assembly may not receive earned income from:
4 (i) an executive unit; or
5 (ii) a political subdivision of the State.
6 (2) The Joint Ethics Committee may exempt an individual from the
7 provisions of paragraph (1) of this subsection if:
8 (I) the earned income is for:
9 (i) 1. educational instruction provided by the member,
10 candidate, or member–elect;
11 (ii) 2. a position that is subject to a merit system hiring process;
12 (iii) 3. a human services position; or
13 (iv) 4. a career promotion, change, or progression that is a logical
14 transition from a pre–existing relationship as described in paragraph (3)(ii) of this
15 subsection; OR
16 5. IF THE INDIVIDUAL HAS SERVED AT LEAST ONE FULL
17 TERM IN THE MARYLAND GENERAL ASSEMBLY OR ON THE GOVERNING BODY OF A
18 POLITICAL SUBDIVISION OF THE STATE, A POSITION FOR WHICH THE INDIVIDUAL
19 OBJECTIVELY SATISFIES THE MINIMUM EDUCATION, LICENSURE, AND EXPERIENCE
20 REQUIREMENTS; AND
21 (II) THE INDIVIDUAL COMPLIES WITH § 5–506 OF THIS
22 SUBTITLE.
23 (3) This subsection does not apply to compensation to a member, candidate,
24 or member–elect derived from:
25 (i) employment as a nonelected law enforcement officer or a fire or
26 rescue squad worker; [or]
27 (ii) a transaction or relationship that existed before the individual:
28 1. filed a certificate of candidacy for election to the General
29 Assembly while the individual was not an incumbent member of the General Assembly; or
30 2. was appointed to fill a vacancy; OR

SENATE BILL 618 3
1 (III) A TRANSACTION OR RELATIONSHIP:
2 1. THAT THE INDIVIDUAL ENTERED INTO AFTER HAVING
3 SERVED AT LEAST ONE FULL ELECTED TERM IN THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY; AND
4 2. FOR WHICH THE INDIVIDUAL HAS OBJECTIVELY
5 SATISFIED THE MINIMUM EDUCATION, LICENSURE, AND EXPERIENCE
6 REQUIREMENTS.
7 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That the Joint Committee on
8 Legislative Ethics shall issue an opinion to provide guidance to the members of the
9 Maryland General Assembly on compliance with this Act, including:
10 (1) necessary actions that a member should take to avoid a conflict of
11 interest; and
12 (2) factors that the Committee will consider when determining whether to
13 grant an exemption under § 5–514(a)(2) of the General Provisions Article, as enacted by
14 Section 1 of this Act.
15 SECTION 2. 3. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
16 October 1, 2026 January 13, 2027.
Approved:
